{"title":"LAMBADA: Backward Chaining for Automated Reasoning in Natural Language","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"LLM-based logical reasoning over natural text struggles with deep, multi-hop proofs: forward-chaining requires combinatorial subset selection and has unclear halting, and models often fail to correctly handle cases where a goal is neither provable nor disprovable (UNKNOWN).","method":"LAMBADA performs backward chaining from the goal and implements each reasoning step with few-shot prompted LM modules: Fact Check (prove/disprove via facts), Rule Selection (identify rules whose consequents unify with the goal), Goal Decomposition (derive sub-goals from rule antecedents), and Sign Agreement (determine PROVED vs DISPROVED based on polarity). It runs depth-first with a max-depth halting criterion and returns UNKNOWN when no applicable rules remain or depth is exhausted, and it reduces search to linear scans over rules/facts instead of combinatorial selection. This approach substantially improves label and proof accuracy on ProofWriter-PUD, PrOntoQA, and ParaRules, especially at depth-5 and on UNKNOWN cases."},{"problem":"Modular forward-chaining systems (e.g., Selection-Inference) become inefficient and error-prone as theories grow—subset selection gets harder, redundant inferences accumulate, and many LM calls are required.","method":"LAMBADA designs two-stage LM submodules to simplify decisions: Fact Check splits into (i) relevant-fact selection and (ii) entailment/contradiction verification; Rule Selection splits into (i) extracting each rule’s consequent and (ii) checking applicability to the goal. It adds a simple reranker that tries shorter rules first, and employs caching plus loop avoidance to prevent redundant work. This yields an efficient depth-first search that makes far fewer LM calls (up to 11.8x fewer than SI at depth-5) and avoids redundant inferences while maintaining accuracy."}]}
